Graphical abstract Highlights âº Organotin compounds as catalysts for urethane formation. âº Ternary complexes between isocyanate, alcohol and catalyst are formed. âº Reaction mechanism depends on type of isocyanates. âº A new mechanism for the urethane formation is proposed. Although organotin carboxylate compounds are widely used in the polyurethane industry as catalysts, their reactions mechanisms are not fully understood. The urethane formation between isocyanate and alcohol groups in the presence of organotin carboxylate catalysts is simulated with selected compounds using computational methods and the results are compared with experimental findings. The results reveal that organotin carboxylate catalysis of the reaction between these isocyanate and n-butanol in a non-polar medium follow two routes depending on the isocyanate structure. The reaction rate for aliphatic primary isocyanates the concentration of the carboxylate ligand in the catalyst has a significant effect while for aromatic isocyanates the effect is much less. Based on experimental and computational results a mechanism is proposed for organotin carboxylate catalysis of urethane formation for these isocyanates. Keywords Organotin compounds Urethane formation DFT Catalyst Isocyanate 1 Introduction Organotin catalysts are widely used in the polyurethane industry due to their outstanding efficiency [1]. The function of the catalyst is to promote the reactivity between the isocyanate and the alcohol groups to form the urethane linkage. Scheme 1 shows the reaction for the urethane formation. Organotin catalysts are generally used in the preparation of polyurethanes based on both aliphatic and aromatic isocyanates. The catalytic effect of organotin compounds on the reactivity of aliphatic isocyanates is much more significant than with aromatic isocyanates [2]. However, due to the wide usage of organotin compounds as catalysts for the industrial synthesis of polyurethanes the subject has been widely investigated to understand the catalytic function in order to gain better control of the reactions concerned [3â7]. Tin in organotin catalysts used in urethane synthesis has a valance state of four. The Sn(IV) is preferentially tetrahedrally coordinated in organotin compounds. However, due to extra 5d orbitals in Sn4+ these compounds could form structures which contain more than four coordinated tin [8]. Sometimes these compounds form dimmeric or polymeric structures through extra coordination [9]. In the organotin carboxylate compounds the carboxylate ligand such as acetic or lauric acid coordinates to tin forming bipyramidal structures [8]. Bloodworh and Davies proposed a catalytic mechanism for organotin compounds in urethane reactions for the first time [4]. In this work phenylisocyanate was reacted with tributyltin methoxide as shown in Scheme 2 . The mechanism proposed was based on the reaction products obtained when phenyl isocyanate reacts with trialkyltin alkoxide. Since then many investigations have carried out and several mechanisms for organotin catalysis in urethane formation have been presented [4â6,10,11]. At present there are three distinct mechanisms suggested for the organotin catalyzed urethane formation: (1) insertion mechanism (organo tin alkoxide intermediate), (2) Lewis acid mechanism and (3) ionic mechanism. Of these, the insertion mechanism is the most accepted in literature [4,6]. In this mechanism the organotin compounds first undergoes alcoholysis to form an intermediate, which becomes the dominant catalyst in the urethane reaction. The Lewis acid mechanism was proposed based on ebullioscopy data [10]. Less evidence exists for the ionic mechanism [8] due to the higher catalytic action shown by this reaction in non-polar media. The above-mentioned mechanisms are derived from indirect data analysis due to a lack of experimental techniques that could monitor reactions during experimentation. Computational methods have the ability to investigate interactions between molecules and hence indicate possible mechanisms. This approach gives a more accurate scenario for the interaction than it can be obtained from experimental procedures. Most of the work reported in literature on the application of computational methods for the investigation of isocyanate chemistry is for the uncatalyzed reaction between isocyanate and alcohol in urethane reactions. These have been done using semi-empirical [12], ab initio [13] and DFT [14â16] methods. Investigations on amine catalysis of urethane formation were only reported using PM3 semi-empirical [17] and DFT methods [18]. Investigation of the catalytic effect of organo-metallic, metal salts and metal chelates using computational methods have received less attention. Here we report computational work on some of the proposed mechanisms related to organotin compounds as catalyst in urethane reaction. A new mechanism for urethane catalysis of organotin carboxylate in lower polar medium is proposed to explain some of the experimental observation to get a better understanding of the catalytic mechanism. 2 Experimental details 2.1 Computational details Interactions between molecules were simulated by bringing the interacting centers close together by a step-by-step fashion while optimizing the total energy of the system at each step. If the total energy of the system went through a maximum, the interaction was considered to have different product to reactants. The structure at the maximum energy was considered as a structure that is close to a transition state. Once the near transition state structure for an interaction is identified it was optimized using the Berny algorithm [19]. The transition state was verified by frequency analysis, which resulted in one negative frequency in all cases. It was further verified related to products form and reactants using IRC (intrinsic reaction coordinate) procedure using the transition state structure [20,21]. The configuration of the molecules on the product side was used to investigate the subsequent interaction between molecules and search for corresponding transition states. This method was repeated until the final products were obtained. The energies of molecular assemblies at minima were calculated as global minima through optimization or single point energy calculation if it was a selected point at the reaction path. In the present work DFT (B3LYP and PBE functionals) and ab initio MP2 calculations were carried out with basis sets 6-31G*, 6-31G**, 6-31+G** for the light elements (C, N, O, H) and LANL2DZ for Sn. However, most of the energy profile calculations were done on DFT/B3LYP/LANL2DZ/6-31G* level of theory in gas phase (unless otherwise stated) to keep the computational costs to a minimum. The calculations were performed by using the program packages Gaussian09 [22] and Spartan10 [23]. All calculated energies are reported as electronic energies at 0K unless otherwise specified. The values reported as Gibbs free energies and enthalpies includes zero point correction at 298K. The influence of solvents was obtained by using a CPCM polarizable conducting model [24,25]. The computational simulations were done using model compounds. Dimethyltin derivatives were used as the model organotin compound and methanol was used as the alcohol and methyl isocyanate or phenyl isocyanate were used as isocyanates. The reason to use these compounds was to reduce the computational costs. Table 1 shows all model compounds and the corresponding reactants that are used in experiments and industrial applications. We assume that the behavior of these molecules will give us the correct trends in behavior of actual compounds. 2.2 Experimental work on reactivity of isocyanate and alcohol in the presence of organotin compound as catalyst Aliphatic and aromatic isocyanates were reacted with alcohol in various quantities in the presence of organotin compounds as catalyst in xylene. The total weights of the reaction mixtures were made to the same weight. The amounts of tin in the reaction mixtures were maintained at constant levels in all experiments. Samples were withdrawn at regular intervals and free isocyanate content in the reaction mix was determined according to the ASTM D2572-97 method [26]. In this method isocyanate first reacted with a known amount of dibutylamine then the isocyanate content was determined by titrating excess amine with standard solution of hydrochloric acid. Desmodur N3390 (isocyanaurettrime of hexamethylenediisocyanate in 10% butyl acetate; Bayer Germany) and Desmodure L75 (adduct of trimethylolpropane and 2,4-toluene diisocyanate in 25% ethyl acetate; Bayer, Germany) were used as the aliphatic and aromatic isocyanate, respectively. Reagent grade n-butanol, (1-methoxy-2-propyl)-acetate, dibutyltin diacetate, glacial acetic acid, xylene (all Merck, Germany) and dibutyltin dibutoxide (Gelest, inc. USA) were used without further purification. Each isocyanate was reacted with varying amounts of n-butanol were reacted at 25Â°C in xylene as the solvent in the presence of selected catalysts. In this set of experiments the isocyanate amount was maintained at 0.274 equivalents and varying amounts of n-butanol were reacted in the presence of 3.768mg tin metal in the selected catalyst. The total volume of the starting reaction mix was maintained at 182mL and 172mL for Desmodur N3390 and Desmodur L75 systems, respectively. 3 Results and discussion 3.1 Simulation of alkoxide formation In literature, the formation of an alkoxide intermediate is proposed to be the active part of the catalyst for organotin(IV) di-substituted catalysis of urethane reactions [4,6]. Scheme 3 indicates the proposed alkoxide formation for organotin(IV) carboxylate catalysis in urethane reaction. Table 2 shows the Gibbs free energy and enthalpy calculated at DFT (B3LYP and PBE, respectively) and MP2 level of theory for the above reaction. The energies were also calculated using CPCM solvent model water and toluene polar and non-polar solvents. They were all calculated including zero point correction at 298K. These values are in reasonable agreement with each other and the positive values obtained for the reaction free energies and enthalpies reveal that the reaction is thermodynamically unfavorable at ambient conditions. By using the LANL2DZ/6-311+G(2df,2p) basis sets B3LYP and PBE results are within a range 2kJmolâ1 for the gas phase, water and toluene calculations (Table 2). At the LANL2DZ/6-31G(d) level, B3LYP and MP2 calculations results are very similar, therefore further MP2 calculations at the higher level have not been conducted. These data also suggest that the influence of the solvent is very minimal. To simulate the interaction between organotin carboxylate and alcohol was done by bringing together oxygen of the alcohol and tin atom of the organotin carboxylate step by step while optimizing the energy. The alcoholysis of DMTDA reaction shown in Scheme 3 was simulated at DFT B3LYP/LANL2DZ/6-31G** level of theory. Because of the self-association of alcohol in non-polar solvents due to hydrogen binding [12], a hydrogen bonded polymeric form of alcohol (three molecules of methanol) was used in the calculations. Fig. 1 shows the energy profile of this interaction. The polymeric form also reduces the bond strain during the reaction. From the energy profile of the interaction it can be seen that the total energy of the system does not go through an energy maximum that would characterize a substitution nucleophilic bimolecular (SN2) type reaction. This would mean that the activation energy for the transfer of hydrogen from methanol to DMTDA to form a methoxideâacedic acid complex reaction could be high, which will not allow the reaction to take place at ambient temperature. The optimized structure for the complex does not show a transition of the hydrogen atom from methanol to DMTDA but a relatively short SnO distance to a methanol molecule has been formed instead (2.35Ã). That leads to a slight elongation of the SnO distances of the carbonyl groups by about 0.1Ã. The free formation energy for the complex obtained after optimization (Fig. 1, inlay) is 14.2kJmolâ1 starting from DMTDA and 3 non hydrogen-bonded molecules methanol. The simulation was also performed using toluene as no-polar and water as polar solvents. These simulations showed similar behaviors to the gas phase calculations. We also extended the calculation to MP2 level of theory with LANL2DZ/6-31G** and LANL2DZ/6-31+G** basis sets. Both gave energy profiles close to those of the DFT calculations. These investigations revel that the alcoholysis step in the interaction between DMTDA and methanol is less likely to happen at ambient conditions. Similar calculations for other organotin compounds such as DMTDmercaptide (dimethyltin dimercaptide) and DMTDC (dimethyltin dichloride), which are commonly used as catalysts in urethane synthesis, did not show a reaction that goes through an energy maximum. Alcoholysis of DMTDA (dimethyltin diacetate) using a single molecule of methanol also shows an energy minimum similar to the polymeric form due to the attraction of the oxygen of methanol to the more positively charged tin atom. Fig. 2 shows the energy profile of this interaction and Table 3 shows the structures of the molecules associated with the interaction. In this simulation DFT B3LYP LANL2DZ/6-31G* level of theory was used (since in the rest of our investigations we used 6-31G* basis set for light elements). However, by using DFT B3LYP/LANL2DZ/6-31G** similar trends in the energy profile were observed as with the 6-31G* basis set for the light elements. It is interesting to see that the energy profile for the interaction between DMTDA and methanol shows two minima, in contrast to the calculations including three molecules of methanol (Fig. 1). We also carried out simulations using PCMC solvent model in toluene and water at DFT B3LYP LANL2DZ/6-31G* level of theory. The solvent calculations resulted in similar trends for the energy profiles as observed for the gas phase. MP2/LANL2DZ/6-31+G** calculations gave very similar results to DFT results. The TS1 transition state (Fig. 2) showed one negative frequency at â38cmâ1. IRC calculations reproduced the starting and final products in the interaction. Further to the above investigation we also carried out the interaction between DMTDA and methanol with other higher energy conformers of DMTDA structures (not reported here). These simulations showed higher energy structures resembles to alkoxide formation when oxygen atom of the alcohol comes close to the tin atom. However, these results show less evidence for their existence from practical observations, which will be discussed later section. The interaction between DMTDA and methanol is discussed next. Fig. 2 shows that the interaction between DMTDA and methanol has two energy minima. In the second minimum the oxygen of the OH group of methanol is associated with the Sn center due to electrostatic attraction (2.47Ã); in this complex the alcohol molecule stays hydrogen-bonded with one of the carboxylic oxygen (1.67Ã). In this situation the chelating carboxylic acid ligand behaves as a carboxylic salt. Both, dimethyltin methoxyacetate and the DMTDA/methanol complex show absorptions around 526cmâ1. These absorptions are due to stretching of the SnO bond as seen in the theoretical spectra. It can be seen that the experimental spectrum resembles the theoretical spectra reasonably well (Fig. 4, top). 3.2 Interaction between various organotin compounds and organic reagents By mixing dibutyltin diacetate (DBTDA) and n-butanol in the molar ratio of 1:2 no significant change in temperature could be observed experimentally. However, mixing of dibutyltin dibutoxide (DBTDbutoxide) and acetic acid at the molar ratio of 1:2 resulted in an exothermal reaction indicating the formation of dibutyltin diacetate. The FTIR-ATR spectrum of the mix of dibutyltin dibutoxide and acetic acid at a molar ration 1:2 was similar to the spectrum of a 1:2 mixture dibutyltin diacetate and n-butanol (Fig. 5 ). The increase in the OH absorption around 3360cmâ1 in the dibutyltin butoxide/acetic acid mixture indicates the formation of alcohol [28], which confirms that the reaction is favored towards the formation of dibutyltin diacetate rather than to the dibutyltin butoxide derivative. This is also confirmed by the absence of strong SnO band found in DBTDbutoxide. Fig. 5 also shows the FTIR-ATR spectra around the SnO stretching region for different compounds. It can be seen that the DBTDA and n-butanol mix does not show absorption around the SnO stretching frequency. This may indicate the absence of the formation of tin alkoxide when organotin carboxylate is mixed with alcohol. These results indicate that an initial formation of alkoxide from an interaction between organotin carboxylate and alcohol is less likely. It can also be said that the subsequent steps suggested are also less likely to happen in the mechanism proposed by Bloodworth and Davies [4] if tin alkoxide is present in an alcohol and isocyanate containing environment. However, since there is less evidence of the formation of organotin alkoxide from organotin dicarboxylate an alternate mechanism is proposed, which will be discussed next. 3.3 Proposed new mechanism to depict the catalytic action of organotin carboxylate catalyst in urethane formation To simulate the interaction between isocyanate and alcohol in the presence of organotin compounds the following method was adopted. Based on the reported work on Lewis interactions the long-range attraction of the negatively charged isocyanate oxygen and the more electropositive tin atom of the organotin carboxylate were taken into consideration. Methyl isocyanate was placed directing the isocyanate oxygen towards the tin atom of the organotin carboxylate. Then the more positively charged isocyanate carbon atom, which shows an unoccupied molecular orbital, was interacted with the highest energy occupied molecular orbital on the oxygen atom of the alcohol group. The two centers were brought together step-by-step. At each step the total energy of the system was minimized. In the absence of explanations for some of the experimentally observed catalytic effects of organotin carboxylate in urethane reactions a new mechanism is proposed to explain the catalysis mechanism. In this model the initial interaction occurred due to the Lewis effect leading to the formation of a ternary complex by interaction between the isocyanate and an alcohol complexed organotin carboxylate. Similar ternary complexes are reported in literature [5,11]. 3.3.1 Aliphatic primary isocyanate catalysis Organotin carboxylate catalysts in an alcohol/isocyanate environment can exist in several molecular assemblies. The possibility of forming a complex between methanol and DMTDA has been already discussed. In this complex the alcohol molecule is associated with the DMTDA and the energy profile indicates the formation of a complexe at the first minimum and more stable complex at the second minimum. The two complexes show Gibbs free energy and enthalpy differences of 18.6kJmolâ1, â19.7kJmolâ1 and 22.1kJmolâ1, â30.6kJmolâ1, respectively, relative to the starting material (calculated at B3LYP/LANL2DZ/6-31G* level of theory). The first complex is considered here since it could undergo further reaction with isocyanate. Calculations for the first complex also show that the HOMO is positioned on the hydrogen-bonded methanol OH with 25.2kJmolâ1 higher energy than the HOMO located on the unassociated methanol OH. A similar mechanism was proposed by Entelis et al. [29] on organotin catalysis of the reaction between isocyanate and alcohol. The higher energy occupied molecular orbital on the OH group will interact with the lowest energy unoccupied molecular orbital of the incoming isocyanate where the isocyanate oxygen is directed towards the tin atom of the organotin complex due to Lewis action. The isocyanate carbon will become more electropositive due to Lewis interaction, which will lead to the formation of a ternary complex. The structure of this ternary complex (index 1) is shown in Table 4 . However, DMTDA, methanol and methyl isocyanate can also form other complexes. The molecular assemblies listed in Table 4 are considered as the most probable interactions. To simplify the model used in the calculations it was assumed that alcohol and isocyanate are present in stoichiometric amounts. The assemblies indexed as 1 and 2 (Table 4) show Gibbs energies and enthalpies of 48.8, â32.3 and 51.0, â40.8kJmolâ1, respectively, obtained from reactions of DMTDA, methyl isocyante and methanol. These complexes have a negative enthalpy and positive Gibbs energy of formation, showing the very strong entropic factor, which is observed in all supramolecular complexes and which can be described as a classical CurtinâHammett situation. Both assemblies could exist due to their very small energy differences (2.2kJmolâ1). The index 1 assembly was selected for further investigation because the molecular arrangement shows a possible interaction between methanol and isocyante to undergo urethane formation. The assembly index 2 was formed as a result of isocyanate interacting with the DMTDA methanol complex that formed at the second minimum. Ternary complexes similar to index 1 could also be formed from higher energy conformers of DMTDA as discussed previously. These also will lead to similar subsequent interaction between these molecules as discussed in the following paragraph. In the molecular assembly the oxygen atom of the isocyanate molecule is attracted towards the tin atom due to Lewis action, which makes the isocyanate carbon more electropositive. This carbon then interacts with the oxygen atom of the alcohol. TS3 is the transition state of the interaction between DMT acetate O-methyl carbamate and methanol, which is present in the reaction mix. This leads to the formation of DMTmethoxy acetate and urethane. Similarly, TS4 is the transition state for the interaction between rearranged DMT acetate O-methyl carbamate, i.e. DMT acetate N-carbamate, and methanol. It can be seen that this reaction has a higher activation energy compared to the interactions discussed previously. In this diagram the energy profile associated with the rearrangement is not shown for clarity. TS5 is the reaction path for the interaction between DMT acetate N-methyl carbamate and acetic acid, which forms DMTDA and urethane. However, in the simulation the acetic acid molecule tend to move away from the tin center during the rearrangement, which makes it less probable for the reaction to take place in the presence of large amount of unreacted alcohol in the reaction mix. From Fig. 7 it is evident that the formation of DMTDA is energetically more favorable than the formation of DMTmethoxy acetate, which means formation of DMTDA and urethane is the most preferred reaction (position marked in Fig. 7; the molecular assembly just after TS1 is shown as inlay). It can be seen that hydrogen atom of the acetic acid molecule that left the DMTDA molecule stays close to the nitrogen atom of the DMTacetate O-methyl carbamate. This will lead to the formation of DMTDA. Since TS4 has a relatively high transition state energy it is possible to say that this reaction path is less probable in a medium rich in alcohol concentration. The high concentration alcohol will prevent formation of N substituted methyl-carbamate. Table S1 shows the corresponding transition state structures. Reaction pathways for more probable reactions were calculated using a CPCM solvent model at DFT B3LYP LANL2DZ/6-31G* level of theory. Fig. 8 shows the energy diagram for the selected reaction in non-polar (toluene) and polar (water) solvents. The final energy difference for the starting material and the products are different for toluene and water by 2.8kJmolâ1 for the formation of DMTDA+urethane (â115.6kJmolâ1 and 112.8kJmolâ1, respectively) and 1.1kJmolâ1 for DMTmethoxy acetate+urethane (â86.8kJmolâ1 and â85.7kJmolâ1, respectively). The gas phase calculation results in reaction enthalpies of â119.4kJmolâ1 (DMTDA+urethane) and â92.3kJmolâ1 (DMTmethoxy acetate+urethane). 3.3.2 Aromatic isocyanate catalysis The mechanism for the interaction of phenyl isocyanates with organotin carboxylate catalysts is similar to that of methyl isocyanates. Fig. 9 shows the atomistic arrangement and the energy diagram for the DMTDA catalyzed reaction between phenyl isocyanate and methanol (the molecular assembly just after TS1 is marked in Fig. 9). It can be seen that the acetic acid and the carbamate nitrogen are on the opposite side of the molecular assembly. Therefore the interaction between these two centers will be much less compared to the same of aliphatic system. Since the acetic acid and the nitrogen of the oxygen-substituted carbamate are in opposite sides of the molecular assembly the oxygen-substituted carbamate could rearrange to nitrogen-substituted carbamate or interact with alcohol in the mixture. TS3 and TS4 are the transition states associated in the interaction between DMTacetate O-phenylcarbamate and methanol. TS2 represents the transition state associated with the interaction between DMTacetate, N-phenylcarbamate, and methanol. This transition state has a higher energy compared to previously discussed reaction path. TS5 is the transition state for the interaction between DMTacetate N-phenylcarbamate and acetic acid. However, as seen in the aliphatic system during the rearrangement of the carbamate the de-attached acetic acid molecule tent to move away from the tin center. This will make this reaction less probable in an environment with high concentration of alcohol. Since the amount of catalyst in the system is much less than the reactant, the acetic acid will not come into the reaction after TS1. Therefore, only the interaction between the DMT acetate O-phenylcarbamate and alcohol was considered. Table S2 shows the corresponding transition state structures. Fig. 10 shows the energy diagram for the DMTDA catalyzed reaction between phenyl isocyanate and methanol in non-polar (toluene) and polar (water) solvents. It can be seen that the polar solvent shows a smaller energy change than the non-polar solvent with higher activation energy (70.7kJmolâ1 and 65.8kJmolâ1). It can also be seen that DMTDA catalyzed overall reaction in polar solvents shows a lesser energy difference from reactant to product than in non-polar solvent (â86.0kJmolâ1 and â85.3kJmolâ1). This indicates the possibility of slower reaction rate in polar solvents. Similar effects are observed experimentally. By comparing the atomic possitions of the two molecular essamblies shown in Figs. 7 and 9 it can be seen that the aliphatic system has a higher digree of probability than the aromatic system for the hydrogen transfer from carboxylic acid to tin carbamate nitrogen. This means the hydrogen transfer step of the aliphatic system will be more effecient. It is also intererasting to note that the atomic charge on the nitrogen atoms of the tin carbamate after the first transition state for the methyl isocyanate system has a slightly higher negative charge (â0.613; NBO) than the phenyl isocyante (â0.580; NBO). The higher negative charge should attract the carboxylate hydrogen more effectively. This situation creastes a condition where the hydrogen transfer will take place depending on the type of isocyanate used. Therefore it is possible for this reaction to follow two different routes depending on the environment and the isocyanate as follows: Step 1 Transfer of the hydrogen to nitrogen of the carbamate group to liberate the urethane molecule and then reforming of the catalyst by combining the organotin methoxy carboxylate with the carboxylic acid group (Scheme 4). Step 2 Interaction of organotin carbamate(I) group to interact with alcohol to form a tin alkoxide (Schemes 5 and 6). As shown in step 1 the carboxylic acid will influence the catalysis function by transferring hydrogen atom to nitrogen of the organotin carbamate to liberate the urethane. In contrast, the carboxylic acid will not influence the function of the catalysis and the subsequent steps will change the organotin carbamate(I) to an organotin alkoxide by reacting with an alcohol molecule as shown in step 2. This will convert all organo carboxylate derivatives to organotin alkoxide derivatives. In the subsequent section the conversion of organotin carbamate to organotin alkoxide derivatives will be discussed, which will be the dominant catalyst for the aromatic isocyanate in urethane formation. Scheme 7 shows the interaction between organotin methoxycarbamate and alcohol to form urethane and the corresponding organotin alkoxide derivatives. In this reaction organotin methoxy O-phenylcarbamate was considered, because experimental investigations have shown that the catalytic reaction of DBTDA was similar to DBTDbutoxide in xylene as discussed in subsequent section. Based on this result we assume that organotin carboxylate converts to organotin alkoxide in non-polar solvents. Fig. 11 shows the energy diagram for the dimethyltin dialkoxide catalyzed reaction between phenyl isocyanate and methanol to form urethane. In this diagram we have only considered the reaction between dimethyltin methoxy O-carbamate and methanol as gas phase reaction. It can be seen that after TS1 the reaction becomes spontaneous. Table S3 shows the corresponding transition state structures. Fig. 12 shows the energy diagram for the reaction in non-polar and polar solvents. From this figure it can be seen that the energy difference for non-polar (toluene) solvent is slightly higher (1.3kJmolâ1) than for polar (water) solvent, which indicates that reaction will be marginally faster in non-polar solvents. Next the catalytic effect of organotinalkoxy derivatives in the urethane formation is discussed. The both forms, organotin dimethoxide and organotin methoxyacetate, will be considered in interactions with methyl isocyanate/methanol and phenyl isocyanate/methanol. The organotin methoxyacetate will function as a catalyst to form urethane by forming a ternary molecular assembly. The ternary complex is formed from a organotin methoxy acetate with methanol, which subsequently interact with a methyl isocyanate to give a ternary complex. It is interesting to see that the tin atom of the alcohol complexed organotin methoxyacetate has higher positive charge (2.319; NBO) than the charge of the tin atom of the un-complexed organotin methoxyacetate (2.283; NBO). Fig. 13 shows the energy profile for the formation of urethanes from both methyl isocyanate and phenyl isocyanates by interacting with methanol when organotin dimethoxide and organotin methoxyacetate compounds are used as catalysts. Since the reaction mixture contains methanol the catalysis is considered to take place through alcohol complexed organotin alkoxide similar to the catalysis of urethane formation with DMTDA as discussed previously. The structures shown in Table 5 are for the DMTmethoxy acetate, methyl isocyanate and methanol products obtained during the reaction. However, details of all species formed are not shown in the energy diagram. From the calculated energy profile it is evident that both aromatic and aliphatic isocyanates show similar trends in the urethane reaction if these catalysts were used and if they were to follow the same mechanism. We have also calculated the energy profiles by first considering the initial interaction being between the tin alkoxide and the isocyanate. The results show that the energy profile has similar trends as before for both types of isocyanates. However, the experimental results indicate different trends for aromatic and primary aliphatic isocyanates, which will be discussed in a subsequent section. 3.3.3 Prediction of reactivity between isocyanate and alcohol in non-polar and polar media Fig. 8 shows the reaction profile for the DMTDA catalyzed reaction between methyl isocyante and methanol in non-polar (toluene) and polar (water) solvents at 0K. The optimized minimum structures and transition states were used to calculate differences in free energies at 298K (including zero-point correction). It is interesting to see that the free energy for reactants and products for path 1, where the reaction regenerates the original catalyst DMTDA, are â54.4kJmolâ1 and â52.6kJmolâ1 in toluene and water, respectively. This means that the reaction rate should become less in polar media for path 1. However, for path 2, where DMTmethoxy acetate is formed, free energies of â30.0kJmolâ1 and â28.3kJmolâ1 for toluene and water media were obtained. This means that in polar media it seems more likely to form more DMTmethoxy acetate intermediate. The free energy of activation for TS1 in non-polar and polar media (by using DMTmethoxy acetate as catalyst) is 141.8 and 132.9kJmolâ1, respectively. By using DMTDA as catalyst the free energies of activation for TS1 are 164.9 and 175.5kJmolâ1 in non-polar and polar media, respectively. This means using DMTmethoxy acetate as catalyst lowers the activation energy in comparison to using DMTDA as the catalyst. Therefore, the reaction rate will increase when moving from non-polar to polar media for aliphatic systems due to the formation of DMTmethoxy acetate. However, for aromatic systems the reaction first follows converting the original catalyst DMTDA to DMTmethoxy acetate as explained previously. The catalytic action will only depend on the activation free energy of the reaction. Calculations show that the activation free energies for TS1 in this reaction are 130.7kJmolâ1 and 141.2kJmolâ1 in non-polar and polar solvents. Similarly, if DMTDmethoxide is functioning as the catalyst the free energies of activation are 139.0kJmolâ1 and 147.0kJmolâ1 in non-polar and polar solvents. The free energies of activation for TS1, when DMTDA is used as a catalyst, are 175.7kJmolâ1 and 182.2kJmolâ1 in non-polar and polar media. This means that the reaction rate may decrease in polar solvents. The reduction of the catalytic effect of organoalkyltin alkokxy derivatives formed when organotin alkoxide is reacted with different molar quantities of carboxylic acid may be due to the poor solubility of the complex formed at transition state in non-polar media for aliphatic isocyanates. The transition state has a higher charge separation for organotin alkoxy derivatives. 3.4 Experimental investigations on reactivity between different isocyanates and alcohol in the presence of organotin compounds as catalyst The following section will discuss the interaction of selected isocyanate of primary aliphatic and aromatic nature, i.e. Desmodur N3390 (isocyanaurettrime of hexamethylenediisocyanate in 10% butyl acetate) and Desmodure L75 (adduct of trimethylolpropane and 2,4-toluene diisocyanate in 25% ethyl acetate) with n-butanol in the presence of organotin derivatives as catalyst in xylene as solvent. Figs. 14 and 15 show the depletion of the isocyanate group (NCO) content of the urethane during the reaction of Desmodur N3390 and Desmodur L75, respectively, with n-butanol by using a set of different catalysts. It can be seen that for primary aliphatic isocyanates the carboxylic group content in the organotin catalyst has a significant effect on the reaction rate (Fig. 14), whereas for aromatic isocyanate no significant influence of the carboxylic group content in the catalyst can be observed (Fig. 15). Figs. 16 and 17 show the effect of alcohol concentration on the reaction rate for the two types of isocyanates when an organotin carboxylate is used as a catalyst. The reaction rate increases with increasing alcohol concentration in the reaction mixture for aromatic isocyanate. However, for aliphatic primary isocyanates increasing alcohol concentration in the reaction mixture has a negative effect on the reaction rate as shown in Fig. 17. The reduction in reaction rate for aliphatic isocyanate with increasing alcohol concentration may be due to the association of the alcohol with DBTDL with excess alcohol will push the equilibrium to the second minimum (see Fig. 2). This will retard the urethane formation due to the formation of the ternary complex that not suitable for urethane reaction as discussed before. In case of aromatic isocyanate with increasing alcohol concentration the conversion of organotin carbamate to organotin alkoxide and the urethane formation will increase. From Figs. 14â17 it is evident that the organotin carboxylate catalysis of primary aliphatic and aromatic isocyanates in urethane formation in a low polar medium takes place by two different mechanisms. It is also possible to say that for primary aliphatic isocyanates in urethane formation with increasing carboxylic acid ligand content in the organotin catalyst will increase the reaction rate. However, for aromatic isocyanates the carboxylic acid content does not significantly affect the reaction rate. Based on computational and experimental results it can be concluded that the reaction between primary aliphatic isocyanate and alcohol takes place as shown in Scheme 4 and for aromatic isocyanatethe reaction will follow a mechanism where the initial catalysis is due to organotin carboxylate as in Scheme 5 and subsequently catalysis is due to organotin alkoxide that is formed as an intermediate as suggested in Schemes 6 and 7 . However, the situation for primary aliphatic isocyanates may change with increasing polarity in the medium, which will drive the mechanism similar to what is shown in Scheme 5. The increase in polarity will prevent the acetic acid molecule staying close to the tin center. 3.5 The reactivity of aliphatic and aromatic isocyanate in non-polar and polar solvents Desmodur N3390 and Desmodur L75 was reacted with n-butanol at stoichiometric amounts in xylene and (1-methoxy-2-propyl)-acetate using DBTDL as catalyst. The reaction was carried out as explained previously starting from constant volume for both solvents. Figs. 18 and 19 show the depletion of NCO content in the reaction mix with time for Desmodur N3390 (aliphatic) and Desmodur L75 (aromatic), respectively. From these figures it can be seen that for aliphatic system reactivity increases and for aromatic system the reactivity decrease changing from xylene to (1-methoxy-2-propyl)-acetate, which is in agreement with results obtained from computational work. The reaction mechanism for primary aliphatic and aromatic isocyanates in urethane formation in the presence of dialkyltin dicarboxylate catalyst in non-polar media can be summarized as shown in Schemes 8 and 9 , respectively. The reaction mechanisms for organotin carboxylate catalysis of secondary and tertiary aliphatic isocyantes in urethane formation will be discussed in a separate paper. 4 Conclusions Computational methods provide a better explanation of experimental results for the organotin carboxylate catalysis of urethane formation. Depending on the type of isocyanate used it is evident that the carboxylic acid ligand contributes to the catalytic function of the organotin dicarboxylate in urethane reactions in less polar media. In such environments organotin carboxylate catalysis of aliphatic isocyanates in urethane formation follows a different mechanism to aromatic isocyanates. Aromatic isocyanates are catalyzed by organotin alkoxide formed as an intermediate while for aliphatic isocyanates the catalysis is mainly due to organotin carboxylate. coredata.dc:description: Although organotin carboxylate compounds are widely used in the polyurethane industry as catalysts, their reactions mechanisms are not fully understood. The urethane formation between isocyanate and alcohol groups in the presence of organotin carboxylate catalysts is simulated with selected compounds using computational methods and the results are compared with experimental findings. The results reveal that organotin carboxylate catalysis of the reaction between these isocyanate and n-butanol in a non-polar medium follow two routes depending on the isocyanate structure. The reaction rate for aliphatic primary isocyanates the concentration of the carboxylate ligand in the catalyst has a significant effect while for aromatic isocyanates the effect is much less. Based on experimental and computational results a mechanism is proposed for organotin carboxylate catalysis of urethane formation for these isocyanates.
